\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Commentary
\emph default
.
 I was stuck here and turned to LLM guidance.
 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{2}+v^{2}$
\end_inset

 (analogous to the real case) doesn't work, because it factors as 
\begin_inset Formula $(u+iv)(u-iv)$
\end_inset

.
 (So 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,i)$
\end_inset

 becomes a solution, as 
\begin_inset Formula $(1+i^{2})(1-i^{2})=(1-1)(1+1)=0(2)=0$
\end_inset

.) Opus 4.5 asks guiding questions to help us get to the proof by contradiction.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $P(u,v)$
\end_inset

 were such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\V(P)=\{(0,0)\}$
\end_inset

.
 We consider the diagonal line 
\begin_inset Formula $u=v$
\end_inset

, which parametrizes as 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,t)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $P(t,t)$
\end_inset

 (subbing in 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 for both 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

) becomes a polynomial in one variable.
 If it vanishes only at the origin, then it has to be of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $c(t-0)^{r}$
\end_inset

.
 But this is also true of any other line through the origin 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,\lambda t)$
\end_inset

, so we have a family 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\lambda}t^{r_{\lambda}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can decompose 
\begin_inset Formula $P(u,v)$
\end_inset

 into same-degree (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

homogenous
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) parts.
 A property of homogenous polynomials of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is that 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{k}(t,\lambda t)=t^{k}P(1,\lambda)$
\end_inset

.
 (You're just 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pulling out
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 all the 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

s.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So if 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is non-homogenous, 
\begin_inset Formula $P(t,\lambda t)=\sum_{j=0}^{\deg(P)}t^{j}P_{j}(1,\lambda)$
\end_inset

, and all but one of the coëfficients 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{j}(1,\lambda)$
\end_inset

 must be zero in order for it to be a pure power.
 But a finite sum of polynomials only has finitely many roots, and we need
 this work for all uncountably many 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Contradiction!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is itself homogenous, then its vanishing set can't just be the origin for
 a different reason.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $P(1,\lambda)$
\end_inset

 has a root, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,\lambda)$
\end_inset

 is a vanishing point besides the origin.
 If it doesn't have a root, then it must be a nonzero constant.
 
\begin_inset Formula $P(1,\lambda)$
\end_inset

 being a nonzero constant (and homogenous of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

) means that we have 
\begin_inset Formula $c=\sum_{j=0}^{k}a_{j}\lambda^{j}(1)^{k-j}=\sum_{j=0}^{k}a_{j}\lambda^{j}$
\end_inset

, so that only 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}$
\end_inset

 is nonzero, which means that for 
\begin_inset Formula $P(u,v)$
\end_inset

, the only nonzero term is 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}u^{k}v^{0}$
\end_inset

, a pure power in 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

, which vanishes at 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,v)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 (which is not just the origin).
 
\end_layout

