\begin_layout Standard
Prompted for a minimal hint to get me unstuck, Gemini Pro 3 suggests change
 of cöordinates: we usually write polynomials as sums of monomials 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

around the origin
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j}c_{j}\prod_{k}x_{k}^{p_{k}}$
\end_inset

, but there's nothing stopping us from defining 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}:=x_{j}-a_{j}$
\end_inset

, which will imply something about the constant term.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So we have a polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, and the only thing we really know about it is that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\vec{a})=0$
\end_inset

.
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}:=x_{j}-a_{j}$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}=y_{j}+a_{j}$
\end_inset

, which we can swap into our polynomial expression whereever 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}$
\end_inset

 appears.
 If we expand all that out, we'll get monomial terms in 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j}c_{j}y_{j}^{p_{j}}$
\end_inset

 (where the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{j}$
\end_inset

s have been absorbed into the constants).
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\vec{a})=0$
\end_inset

 implies that the constant term of that polynomial (in terms of the 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}$
\end_inset

) is zero.
 But then when we undo the substitution back into terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j}c_{j}(x_{j}-a_{j})^{p_{j}}$
\end_inset

, which is the form we were looking for that shows the polynomial is in
 the relevant ideal.
