 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\I(\V(x^{2}+y^{2}-1))$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
i
\series default
.
 We want to show that there exist 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1},g_{2}\in\R[x]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f-g_{1}-yg_{2}\in\left\langle x^{2}+y^{2}-1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I originally wrote down some confused thoughts here, which are moot because
 I had accidentally transcribed the 
\begin_inset Formula $-yg_{2}$
\end_inset

 term as 
\begin_inset Formula $-g_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Gemini 3 Pro says we should be thinking about polynomial long division
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\R[x][y]$
\end_inset

: the doctrine of polynomial long division says we can divide 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}+y^{2}-1$
\end_inset

 with some remainder: we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f=q(x^{2}+y^{2}-1)+r$
\end_inset

, which is 
\begin_inset Formula $f-r=q(x^{2}+y^{2}-1)$
\end_inset

 (and then 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is going to turn out to be zero, which will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}+y^{2}-1$
\end_inset

, which will show that it's in the ideal).
 The division drops the degree, so 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 must be degree-zero-or-one in 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That is, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,y)-g_{1}(x)-yg_{2}(x)=q(x,y)(x^{2}+y^{2}-1)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
ii
\series default
.
 Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0},y_{0}$
\end_inset

 on the unit circle.
 Then we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\cancel{f(x_{0},y_{0})}-g_{1}(x_{0})-y_{0}g_{2}(x_{0})=\cancel{q(x,y)(x^{2}+y^{2}-1)}$
\end_inset

, so we have 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}g_{2}(x_{0})=-g_{1}(x_{0})$
\end_inset

.
 We can square that (as one should not need an LLM to point out, seriously)
 to get 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}^{2}g_{2}(x_{0})^{2}=g_{1}(x_{0})^{2}$
\end_inset

, and then 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-x_{0}^{2})g_{2}(x_{0})^{2}=g_{1}(x_{0})^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
iii
\series default
.
 By unique factorization, 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}(x_{0})^{2}$
\end_inset

 has to split into two factors of the same degree.
 And the same is true of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}(x_{0})^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-x_{0}^{2})$
\end_inset

 is of even degree, so that doesn't itself show that there's no solution
 other than 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}=g_{2}=0$
\end_inset

, because 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 could have degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 could have degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d-2$
\end_inset

 ...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Gemini 3 Pro points out that the multiplicity of any factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}^{2}$
\end_inset

 must be even, but the multiplicity of 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-x_{0}^{2})$
\end_inset

 is odd.
 The mismatch means that 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}=g_{2}=0$
\end_inset

 is the only solution.
